        "title": "68th Annual Biosafety and Biosecurity Conference",
        "summary": "No summary available",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.labroots.com/virtual-event/68th-annual-biosafety-biosecurity-conference?id=9578",
        "date": "27-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "This European treatment for joint pain just passed a major scientific test",
        "summary": "Korean researchers found that low-dose radiation therapy eased knee pain and improved movement in people with mild to moderate osteoarthritis.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015032316.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Exercise might be the key to a younger, sharper immune system",
        "summary": "Endurance exercise may train the immune system as much as the muscles.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251014014421.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Popular hair-loss pill linked to depression and suicide",
        "summary": "Finasteride, a common hair-loss drug, has long been tied to depression and suicide, but regulators ignored the warnings.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040343.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A single protein could stop sudden death after heart attacks",
        "summary": "A team at Massachusetts General Hospital uncovered that an immune defense protein, Resistin-like molecule gamma, attacks heart cells after a heart attack—literally punching holes in them.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040341.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "C-section births linked to sleepless nights and painful recoveries",
        "summary": "Women who undergo C-sections are more likely to experience debilitating pain and sleep disorders in the months after giving birth.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040331.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Fentanyl overdoses among seniors surge 9,000% — A hidden crisis few saw coming",
        "summary": "Overdose deaths from fentanyl mixed with stimulants have skyrocketed among seniors, increasing 9,000% in just eight years.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251012054606.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Two common drugs could reverse fatty liver disease",
        "summary": "Researchers at the University of Barcelona found that combining pemafibrate and telmisartan significantly reduces liver fat and cardiovascular risks in MASLD models.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251011105531.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "MIT’s “stealth” immune cells could change cancer treatment forever",
        "summary": "MIT and Harvard scientists have designed an advanced type of immune cell called a CAR-NK cell that can destroy cancer while avoiding attack from the body’s own immune defenses.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251011043535.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists unlock nature’s secret to a cancer-fighting molecule",
        "summary": "Researchers have cracked the code behind how plants make mitraphylline, a rare cancer-fighting molecule.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251009033206.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists discover brain circuit that can switch off chronic pain",
        "summary": "Scientists have pinpointed Y1 receptor neurons in the brain that can override chronic pain signals when survival instincts like hunger or fear take precedence. Acting like a neural switchboard, these cells balance pain with other biological needs.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251009033126.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Common medications may secretly rewire your gut for years",
        "summary": "Drugs taken years—even decades—ago can leave lasting imprints on the gut microbiome, reshaping the community of microbes long after treatment stops.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251008030953.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists reveal green tea’s fat-burning secret",
        "summary": "New research shows green tea may help the body burn fat and balance blood sugar.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251008030951.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists just found a molecule that could stop Parkinson’s in its tracks",
        "summary": "Researchers have designed a peptide that prevents the deadly misfolding of alpha-synuclein, the protein behind Parkinson’s and some dementias. In lab and animal tests, it stabilized the protein and improved motor function. The work demonstrates the power of rational drug design in tackling brain diseases that have long lacked effective treatments.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251008030949.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "New pill could finally control stubborn high blood pressure",
        "summary": "A new pill called baxdrostat may offer hope for people whose blood pressure stays high even after taking standard medications.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251008030947.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Bacteria hidden inside tumors could help beat cancer",
        "summary": "Scientists have discovered that bacteria living inside tumors can produce a molecule that fights cancer and enhances chemotherapy.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251007081835.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Nanotech transforms vinegar into a lifesaving superbug killer",
        "summary": "Researchers have enhanced vinegar’s antibacterial properties by infusing it with cobalt-based carbon nanoparticles.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251006051122.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Brain cancer that eats the skull stuns scientists",
        "summary": "A new study shows glioblastoma isn’t confined to the brain—it erodes the skull and hijacks the immune system within skull marrow. The cancer opens channels that let inflammatory cells enter the brain, fueling its deadly progression. Even drugs meant to protect bones can make things worse, highlighting the need for therapies that target both brain and bone. The discovery reframes glioblastoma as a whole-body disease, not just a brain disorder.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251005085618.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Doctors stunned by a cheap drug’s power against colon cancer",
        "summary": "A Scandinavian clinical trial has revealed that low-dose aspirin can halve the risk of colon and rectal cancer recurrence in patients with specific genetic mutations.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251003033921.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A single dose of psilocybin may rewire the brain for lasting relief",
        "summary": "Penn researchers found that psilocybin can calm brain circuits tied to pain and mood, easing both physical suffering and emotional distress in animal studies. The compound works in the anterior cingulate cortex, bypassing injury sites and offering a dual benefit for pain and depression. Unlike opioids, psilocybin is non-addictive and may provide relief lasting weeks.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251002073959.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A common supplement could supercharge cancer treatments",
        "summary": "Zeaxanthin, best known for eye health, has been found to boost the tumor-killing power of T cells.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251001092214.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "From poison to power: How lead exposure helped shape human intelligence",
        "summary": "Scientists studying ancient teeth found that early humans, great apes, and even Neanderthals were exposed to lead millions of years ago. Long before humans built cities or wrote words, our ancestors may have faced a hidden threat that shaped who we became.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015230952.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Tiny brain nanotubes found by Johns Hopkins may spread Alzheimer’s",
        "summary": "Johns Hopkins scientists uncovered microscopic “nanotube” channels that neurons use to transfer toxic molecules. While this process clears waste, it can also spread harmful proteins like amyloid-beta.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015230939.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists find the brain’s hidden pulse that may predict Alzheimer’s",
        "summary": "Researchers at USC have created the first method to noninvasively measure microscopic blood vessel pulses in the human brain. Using advanced 7T MRI, they found these tiny pulsations grow stronger with age and vascular risk, disrupting the brain’s waste-clearing systems.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251014014418.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Supercharged vitamin k could help the brain heal itself",
        "summary": "Researchers have synthesized enhanced vitamin K analogues that outperform natural vitamin K in promoting neuron growth. The new compounds, which combine vitamin K with retinoic acid, activate the mGluR1 receptor to drive neurogenesis.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251014014312.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists build artificial neurons that work like real ones",
        "summary": "UMass Amherst engineers have built an artificial neuron powered by bacterial protein nanowires that functions like a real one, but at extremely low voltage. This allows for seamless communication with biological cells and drastically improved energy efficiency.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040335.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Dolphins may be getting Alzheimer’s from toxic ocean blooms",
        "summary": "Dolphins washing up on Florida’s shores may be victims of the same kind of brain degeneration seen in humans with Alzheimer’s disease. Researchers discovered that cyanobacterial toxins—worsened by climate change and nutrient pollution—accumulate in marine food chains, damaging dolphin brains with misfolded proteins and Alzheimer’s-like pathology.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251011105521.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Breakthrough compounds may reverse nerve damage caused by multiple sclerosis",
        "summary": "Researchers have identified two compounds, K102 and K110, that could repair the nerve damage from multiple sclerosis. These drugs help regenerate the protective myelin sheath and balance immune responses.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251011102259.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "For the first time, scientists pinpoint brain cells linked to depression",
        "summary": "Scientists identified two types of brain cells, neurons and microglia, that are altered in people with depression. Through genomic mapping of post-mortem brain tissue, they found major differences in gene activity affecting mood and inflammation.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251010091559.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists suggest the brain may work best with 7 senses, not just 5",
        "summary": "Scientists at Skoltech developed a new mathematical model of memory that explores how information is encoded and stored. Their analysis suggests that memory works best in a seven-dimensional conceptual space — equivalent to having seven senses. The finding implies that both humans and AI might benefit from broader sensory inputs to optimize learning and recall.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251008030955.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists finally reveal what’s behind long COVID’s mysterious brain fog",
        "summary": "Researchers in Japan have pinpointed a biological cause of Long COVID brain fog using advanced PET brain imaging. They discovered widespread increases in AMPA receptor density linked to cognitive impairment and inflammation. The findings confirm brain fog as a measurable, biological condition and reveal new targets for treatment. This could open the door to effective diagnostics and therapies.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251006051127.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists find brain circuit that traps alcohol users in the vicious cycle of addiction",
        "summary": "Addiction often isn’t about chasing pleasure—it’s about escaping pain. Researchers at Scripps Research have discovered that a tiny brain region called the paraventricular nucleus of the thalamus (PVT) becomes hyperactive when animals learn that alcohol eases the agony of withdrawal. This circuit helps explain why people relapse: their brains learn that alcohol brings relief from stress and anxiety.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251006051124.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists find hidden brain damage behind dementia",
        "summary": "A University of New Mexico scientist is revealing what might be one of the most overlooked causes of dementia — damage in the brain’s tiny blood vessels. Dr. Elaine Bearer has created a new way to classify these changes, showing that many people diagnosed with Alzheimer’s also suffer from vascular damage that quietly destroys brain tissue. Even more surprising, she’s finding microplastics inside the brain that appear linked to inflammation and memory loss.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251005085637.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Why ultra-processed foods aren’t the real villain behind overeating",
        "summary": "Researchers from Leeds found that overeating is driven more by what people believe about food than by its actual ingredients or level of processing. Foods perceived as fatty, sweet, or highly processed were more likely to trigger indulgence. Surprisingly, the “ultra-processed” label explained almost none of the difference in overeating behavior. The findings suggest that perception and psychology may be more important than packaging or processing.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251005085625.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Why the brain’s GPS fails with age, and how some minds defy it",
        "summary": "Stanford scientists found that aging disrupts the brain’s internal navigation system in mice, mirroring spatial memory decline in humans. Older mice struggled to recall familiar locations, while a few “super-agers” retained youthful brain patterns. Genetic clues suggest some animals, and people, may be naturally resistant to cognitive aging. The discovery could pave the way for preventing memory loss in old age.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251005085616.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Strong friendships may literally slow aging at the cellular level",
        "summary": "Scientists discovered that lifelong social support can slow biological aging. Using DNA-based “epigenetic clocks,” they found that people with richer, more sustained relationships showed younger biological profiles and lower inflammation. The effect wasn’t about single friendships but about consistent connections across decades.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251004092917.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Hidden cellular “power switch” could transform Parkinson’s treatment",
        "summary": "Researchers uncovered a key cellular regulator, PP2A-B55alpha, that controls both the cleanup of damaged mitochondria and the creation of new ones. In Parkinson’s disease models, reducing this regulator improved symptoms and mitochondrial health. The findings could inspire new drugs for Parkinson’s, mitochondrial disorders, and even cancer.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251004092903.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "They found the switch that makes the body attack cancer",
        "summary": "Scientists have found a way to transform hard-to-treat tumors into targets for the immune system.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015230959.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A giant asteroid hit Earth, but its crater is missing",
        "summary": "Researchers discovered a new field of ancient tektites in South Australia, revealing a long-forgotten asteroid impact.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015230957.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "This type of meat supercharges muscle growth after workouts",
        "summary": "Scientists discovered that lean pork builds muscle more effectively post-workout than high-fat pork, even with identical protein levels.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015032318.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A little stress could be the secret to healthy aging",
        "summary": "Scientists discovered that specific nutrients in nematodes' diets activate stress defenses that keep their cells healthier over time.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015032314.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists grow mini human livers that predict toxic drug reactions",
        "summary": "A new human liver organoid microarray developed by Cincinnati Children’s and Roche recreates immune-driven liver injury in the lab.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251015032259.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A simple fatty acid could restore failing vision",
        "summary": "Scientists at UC Irvine have found a way to potentially reverse age-related vision loss by targeting the ELOVL2 “aging gene” and restoring vital fatty acids in the retina.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251014014307.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Your brain’s power supply may hold the key to mental illness",
        "summary": "Groundbreaking Harvard research is exposing hidden energy failures inside brain cells that may drive major psychiatric conditions.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251014014304.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "This new blood test can catch cancer 10 years early",
        "summary": "Scientists at Mass General Brigham have created HPV-DeepSeek, a blood test that can detect HPV-linked head and neck cancers nearly a decade before diagnosis.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040337.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Your skin could warn of hidden mental health trouble",
        "summary": "People experiencing their first psychotic episode who also have skin conditions such as rashes or itching are at greater risk of depression and suicidal thoughts.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040328.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "This experimental “super vaccine” stopped cancer cold in the lab",
        "summary": "UMass Amherst researchers have developed a groundbreaking nanoparticle-based cancer vaccine that prevented melanoma, pancreatic, and triple-negative breast cancers in mice—with up to 88% remaining tumor-free.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251013040323.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists found a smarter Mediterranean diet that cuts diabetes risk by 31%",
        "summary": "Spanish researchers found that combining a calorie-reduced Mediterranean diet with exercise and professional support cut type 2 diabetes risk by 31%.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251012054621.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "New research reveals how ADHD sparks extraordinary creativity",
        "summary": "Researchers have discovered that ADHD’s hallmark mind wandering might actually boost creativity.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251012054608.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Your type of depression could shape your body’s future health",
        "summary": "Different types of depression affect the body in different ways.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251012054604.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Keto diet shields young minds from early-life trauma",
        "summary": "Young rats given a ketogenic diet were largely protected from the mental and behavioral issues caused by prenatal stress.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251012054601.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Scientists find gold hiding in food waste",
        "summary": "Researchers are finding extraordinary new uses for what we throw away.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251011105518.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "How 1 in 4 older adults regain happiness after struggling",
        "summary": "A University of Toronto study found that nearly one in four adults aged 60+ who reported poor well-being were able to regain optimal wellness within three years.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251010091600.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A toxic Alzheimer’s protein could be the key to fighting cancer",
        "summary": "A surprising link between Alzheimer’s and cancer reveals that amyloid beta, a harmful protein in the brain, actually empowers the immune system.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251010091555.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "MIT’s new precision gene editing tool could transform medicine",
        "summary": "MIT scientists have found a way to make gene editing far safer and more accurate — a breakthrough that could reshape how we treat hundreds of genetic diseases.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251010091553.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "When men drink, women and children pay the price",
        "summary": "Men’s heavy drinking is fueling a hidden crisis affecting millions of women and children worldwide.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251010091550.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A hidden “backup heater” that helps burn fat and boost metabolism",
        "summary": "Scientists have uncovered a surprising new way the body can burn energy and stay warm.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251009033247.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Thousands fall ill as mosquito fever explodes across southern China",
        "summary": "China’s Guangdong Province is battling its worst-ever chikungunya outbreak, with thousands of infections spreading across major cities and nearby regions.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251009033244.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A sweet fix for baldness? Stevia compound boosts hair growth",
        "summary": "Researchers discovered that stevioside, a compound from the Stevia plant, enhances the skin absorption of minoxidil, the main treatment for pattern baldness.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251009033212.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A psychedelic surprise: DMT helps the brain heal after stroke",
        "summary": "Scientists have discovered that DMT, a natural compound found in plants and even the human brain, can dramatically reduce brain damage caused by stroke.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251006051129.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "You don’t have to lose weight to lower your diabetes risk, scientists say",
        "summary": "A major study from Tübingen found that prediabetic individuals who normalized their blood sugar through healthy habits — even without shedding pounds — cut their risk of type 2 diabetes by 71%.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251006051117.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "A flu test you can chew",
        "summary": "Flu detection could soon be as simple as chewing gum.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251002074011.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Millions could be living with hidden smell loss after COVID without knowing",
        "summary": "A massive NIH-backed study reveals that COVID-19’s toll on smell may be more widespread and lasting than most realize.",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2025/10/251002074007.htm",
        "date": "25-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "xMAP Connect 2025 Virtual Series",
        "summary": "No summary available",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.labroots.com/virtual-event/xmap-connect-2025-virtual-series?id=9612",
        "date": "22-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "CRISPR Virtual Event Series 2025",
        "summary": "No summary available",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.labroots.com/virtual-event/crispr-2025?id=8604",
        "date": "22-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Marijuana Linked to Fewer Opioid Overdoses",
        "summary": "How can cannabis legalization laws impact opioid use? This is what a recent study published in the American Journal of H ...",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.labroots.com/trending/cannabis-sciences/29720/marijuana-linked-fewer-opioid-overdoses-2",
        "date": "16-10-2025"
    },
    {
        "title": "Hormone Replacement Therapy Restores Healthy Immune Response",
        "summary": "Hormone replacement therapy (HRT) or menopausal hormone therapy (MHT) are treatments to mediate symptoms of menopause. P ...",
        "hyperlink": "https://www.labroots.com/trending/immunology/29717/hormone-replacement-therapy-restores-healthy-immune-response",
        "date": "16-10-2025"
